    "title": "Integrative Close: Calculating Circuit Current from Field Data",
    "objective": "Synthesize statistical averaging, unit conversion using indices, and formula transposition to determine the operating current of an electrical load.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "To find the actual operating current of a load in a real-world scenario, you must often combine several mathematical steps. First, you calculate a mean (average) voltage from multiple test readings to ensure accuracy. Second, you must handle indices by converting power ratings from kilowatts (kW) into base Watts (W). Finally, you apply the 'Golden Rule' of transposition to rearrange the power formula (P = V × I) to solve for the unknown current (I).",
      "This process ensures that your final calculation is based on representative data and correct mathematical relationships, which is vital for selecting the correct cable and protection sizes."
    ],
    "questionText": "You are testing a heater rated at 3.45kW. You have taken three voltage readings at the terminals: 225V, 230V, and 235V. Calculate the mean voltage, convert the power rating to Watts, and then use the transposed power formula (P = V × I) to find the final operating current (I) in Amps.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "Mean Voltage = 230V (225 + 230 + 235 divided by 3)",
      "Power = 3,450W (3.45 x 1,000 or 10³)",
      "Transposed Formula: I = P / V",
      "Final Current = 15A (3,450 / 230)"
    ],
    "hint": "First, find the average of the three voltages. Then, remember that 'kilo' means multiply by 1,000. Finally, divide your power in Watts by your average voltage to find the Amps."
  }
